Federal Budget Analysis for the 8th Period of 2025¶

By Max Yefimov¶

Dataset¶

This dataset was taken directly from the United States government spending website, USAspending.gov. This is publically available data that allows anyone to download the budgets for different agencies within the United States. In this case, the period was marked as FY2025P08 (Fiscal Period 2025, Period 8).¶

Intro¶

This project explores how public funds are allocated and spent across U.S. federal agencies using real financial data from USAspending.gov. The goal is to uncover patterns in budgeting, identify potential inefficiencies, and evaluate how different agencies use their allocated funds.¶

Although this project was primarily done to practice SQL within context, this analysis was designed to answer real business questions, similar to the work real business/data analysts might do. Through a series of SQL-based challenges, I examined:¶

Which agencies commit the most funding?¶

Which programs are spending more than they were budgeted?¶

Which accounts are underutilizing their available resources?¶

How efficiently are departments turning allocated budgets into real spending?¶

This data comes from a single submission period but is very in depth with financial records across all major U.S. agencies. The project involved normalized database tables, importing raw CSV files, and writing queries to answer questions about the data.¶

Tools used: PostgreSQL, Excel (for cleaning), pgAdmin, SQL¶

Key skills demonstrated:¶

- Financial data analysis¶

- SQL joins, aggregates, case logic¶

- Performance benchmarking and budget efficiency analysis¶

Question 4: High Unobligated Balances Relative to Total Budget¶

This query reveals which accounts have high unobligated balances relative to their total budgets. The limit chosen was 0.25, where if more than 25% of the total budget is unobligated for a specific account, that is considered high and each row that fills this criteria is listed. The results could highlight potential underutilization of resources. When a significant portion of allocated funds is not obligated, it may suggest inefficiency, over-budgeting, bureaucratic delays, or a mismatch between planned and actual spending. Identifying these cases helps financial managers and policymakers adjust future budgets or investigate process bottlenecks. Alternatively it could also be an indicator of accounts and functions that are reserved for immense flexibility in order to address emergencies or situations as they come up.¶

Result:¶

As witnessed here a lot of rows do feature entirely unobligated budgets which may be a sign of them being underdeveloped logistically and legally with their appropriate bills. Included in the code is also a prevention to division by 0 to catch accounts that didn't actually have anything assigned to them this period but still spent money due to carryover from previous periods. Several of these rows in future analysis could be filtered further to identify areas of government spending that lack proper development or are entirely irrelevant and could be cut to save costs if needed.¶

Question 5: Gross Outlay Efficiency Ratio¶

Efficiency ratios reveal how well public funds are being used. A ratio near or above 1 means an account is executing on its budget, while lower ratios indicate lagging or underutilized programs. In financial services, similar KPIs help determine operational effectiveness and performance health. This analysis promotes transparency and also highlights the rolling nature of government spending that creates interesting results.¶

SQL Code:¶

Result:¶

This table at first seemed very wrong to me, as the ratio should not be above 1. I even went through several of these accounts to see if there was an error of the data, however everything was consistent. Therefore I had to research an explanation as to why this ratio could look like this:¶

Possible Explanations:¶

Multi-year spending: An account might spend money allocated in previous years, so current outlays exceed current year's budgetary resources¶
Reimbursements and transfers: Accounts can receive additional funding mid-year that wasn't in the original budget¶
Obligation vs. outlay timing: Budget resources might be obligated in one period but the actual cash outlay happens later¶
Supplemental appropriations: Congress can provide additional funding beyond the initial budget¶

This analysis highlights how government spending is different from the pure yearly number and demonstrates the nuances within the different perspectives that can be used to examine the raw data.¶

Conclusion¶

This project was created to test and practice my SQL skills through the exploration of US federal government budget allocation, utilization, and spending. I normalized the data set within Microsoft Excel and created questions about the data that could be solved through SQL queries which in turn highlighted operational differences, agency performances, and a quantification of how funds are utilized by the government across accounts and subfunctions.¶

The analysis ranged from basic SQL queries to more involved classfication logic and bucketing and in turn prompted more nuanced business questions like the ability of an agency to overspend their budget, why certain agencies were obligated to spend more and some were entirely flexible, and the differences in operational structure based on the transaction volume and average spend size.¶

During the development of this project I emphasized including critical thinking and interpretation in between writing code. Although I didn't have a set problem to solve with this data and therefore couldn't create specific suggestions as would be typical in a data analyst role, I hoped to offer insight into further paths that could be taken with specific questions that could be used to identify problems and in turn create solutions. I was using government data, however these exact same principles can very easily be applied to the private sector where I hope to work some day.¶

My dataset was limited to a single reporting period which not only limited the amount of data I actually had, but also the amount of context I could use. However, it was a good basis for my aforementioned critical thinking goals. If extended across multiple periods the dataset could be used as a basis for time-series analysis and forecasting, which in turns lends itself to visualization software like Tableau.¶

If I had to improve this project, that would be the next major step I would take. Although tables are useful for seeing the raw numbers, including visualization would instantly make the data much more readable.¶

Ultimately this project demonstrates my confidence with parts of the SQL language, but also my want and ability to extract insight and stories from data. Thank you for reading!¶
